<h1>@HI{{tokoroga}}</h1>

<h2> Formation </h2>

<ol>
<li> @Vta{{}} <strong>@HI{{tokoroga}}</strong>
</ol>

<h2> Definition </h2>

<p>
@HI{{tokoroga}} always follows @Vta{{}} even though its tense is not necessarily in the past and depends on the tense
of the verb in the main clause.
</p>

<p>
@HI{{tokoroga}} is used between two clauses to show that they have opposite meanings. The result is often unexpected (although
it may be good or bad).
</p>

<h2> Examples </h2>

<ol>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    @HI{{ano@KJ{{person}}ni@KJ{{meeting}}ini@KJ{{going}}tta<strong>tokoroga</strong>,@KJ{{meeting^deliberation^in}}
    de@KJ{{meeting}}enakatta.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    I went to see her but I couldn't because she was in a meeting.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
<li>
<table class="sentence" border=0>
  <tr class="jp"> <td>
    @HI{{amari@KJ{{period^wait}}shitenakatta<strong>tokoroga</strong>,sono@KT{{konsa-to}}hasubarashikatta.}}
  </td> </tr>
  <tr class="en"> <td>
    Although I hadn't been expecting much, the concert was fabulous.
  </td> </tr>
</table>
</ol>


